So the first grey hairs may have started appearing now, and I’m getting very crinkly around the eyes, but so far the 4th decade of my like has been the best!

Next year already looks to be an exciting one so roll on 41, I’m so ready for you!!

We had a little festive disaster yesterday.

We had just finished our delicious Christmas lunch and were mid dishwasher load when there was the most almighty crash!

The top of our kitchen shelves had fallen off the wall, taking with it the 2 shelves below and a good chunk of our preserved food stores.

Swipe to see the carnage, honestly it was like a food and glass bomb had gone off and managed to spread to nearly every corner of the room.

A solid 2 hour clean up followed, that included chipping off the glass shard riddled cement that the flour and jam had combined to create.

Really a lot of fun, just when we had designs of xmas day naps on the sofa.

Im not going to lie, I’m a little gutted, nothing that we lost was of significant value though we had been solidly investing in our jar collection all year, it is more the time and months of effort all lost in the blink of an eye.

Anyway, we live and learn and I’m not the kind of person to let these things get to me.
We will reinforce the shelves and its a great excuse to grow even more next year.

I do hope you had a less eventful Christmas Day than we did!

I’ve taken a few days to digest our program airing on Channel 5 last week and I still don’t think it’s properly sunk in.

Being honest I was utterly terrified of it coming out, the production company had warned us to prepare for negativity along with the positive, and that’s something I just don’t deal with well.

What we actually received was the most overwhelmingly and joyous outpouring of love and support for the life we have worked so hard to build.

I am so blown away by the response and I just wanted to say a massive thank you to you all for being utterly wonderful.

This global community of IG gardeners is a truly special thing and I feel privileged to be a part of it and have your support, thank you! 

I’m still working my way through all your messages so if I haven’t got back to you yet, I’m sorry, I’m getting through them and I want to take the time to appreciate each and every beautiful message of support.

Big love to you all, I can’t wait to share this first full year on the homestead with you guys 💚

It’s forcing time baby!
After giving my 12 rhubarb crowns last year to establish in their new home, I have placed forcers over the strongest 2 crowns.

For those that have no idea what this is, this will result in an early harvest of very long sweet neon pink rhubarb stems with barely any leaf.

After that these 2 crowns will get a couple of years off to rest and grow as normal before I force them again.

Yum! I can practically taste the crumble and cake to come already!!

The day lilies for my @bbcgwlive show garden arrived last week so I potted them up asap.
 
Day lilies are a fabulous edible flower that can be eaten at crunchy bud or fleshy full bloom stage. You can even dry and powder the withered old flowers to use as a seasoning on food.

As if that wasn’t good enough they are a seriously beautiful garden plant and will form a vital part of the floral display in my show garden.

I have gone for a selection of different varieties but all either flower in shades of peach and coral, or in dramatic jet black.

So with such an important role to play it was important to get them potted up and establishing so they will be at their peak for show time.

Do you struggle with fungus gnats (scarid fly)?
I definitely do and I think a lot of people have the same problem though I don’t see it talked about that much.

If you have them you are not doing anything wrong, the eggs are present in the vast majority of commercial compost and out in nature these little flies would fulfil a beneficial composting role.

The problem comes when you are trying to propagate because the tiny maggots that live in the soil love nothing more than feasting on seeds and seedling roots.

So if you have ever had a tray of seeds mysterious not germinate and a curious quantity of what you thought were fruit fly, these little beasties may well have been to blame.

They are really easy to treat organically with nematodes, microscopic worms that are totally harmless to humans, pets, edible plants and basically every other being other than the one that they are bred to attack.

Just stir that powder into water and dilute as per instructions and water on, job done, you can’t even overdose like you can with plant food so you don’t have to stress.
Those tiny worms will move about the soil, attacking only the fungus gnat maggots.
Treat again in 2 weeks to get rid of any newly hatched grubs, personally I treat fortnightly all through propagation season as I will constantly be opening new bags of compost.

I’ll share more of how I treat my pests (yes I get lots too) with organic methods if that would be helpful, just drop a comment 👇🏻 

Thanks to @basf_nemasys_uk for sending me their fruit and veg nematodes so I could make this reel for you, but to be clear this is a product that I buy regularly and use every single year, I couldn’t do without it!

Want strong plants? Then you got to shake it out!

Indoor grown plants have never faced the harsh realities of outdoor life like wind and rain, so they can be a bunch of softies.

It might look brutal but it is just a bit of tough love that really works.
A very good idea if you don’t want to be staking all your sunflowers and kale all year!

Want big bushy pepper and chilli plants with heaps of fruit?
Well then it’s off with their heads!

Plants have growth hormone just like we do, and in seedlings it is concentrated in that top tip.
If you nip it off the tip, drastic as it may look, it tells the plant to redistribute that growth hormone to all the nodes further down the stem.

Give it a week or two and you will see branches starting to pop out all the way down the stem.

More branches mean more places for the plant to flower which ultimately mean more fruit at harvest time.

It’s another win for the tough love approach.

You already know I’m not a fan of grass.
Unless you are a football player or farmer, it tends to be a high maintenance monoculture that does it’s best to die in any extreme of weather.

What’s not to love there?

Other ‘useful’ lawn alternatives I have installed around the homestead are creeping thyme and creeping camomile.
Both are edible, self seeding, beneficial to pollinators and smell incredible when you walk over them.

Do you have lots of really tiny garlic?

Tiny garlic cloves can be too fiddly to bother peeling each time you want to cook but that doesn’t mean it should go to waste.

This is what I do with mine:
Peel the bulbs until you get down to a layer that is still tender and not dried out yet.
It is also a nice quick way to clean them up.

Chop off the roots and any tough base that they are attached to, again until you are down to the tender parts.

If the leaves are still tender and green you can keep some of these too, they still taste garlicky.

Now pass the whole lot through the grater fitting on a food processor, they can go in whole, no need to chop or separate those fiddly cloves.
Obviously you can do this by hand but it’s going to take much longer and you’ll probably smell of garlic for the rest of your life!

The end result is a whole load of rough chopped garlic for the freezer that you can add straight to cooking whenever you are ready.

This is also a good solution for bulbs that didn’t split into cloves, or garlic hit by the dreaded leaf miner.

Anyone else got a way to use problem garlic?

Have you got lots of bolted onions?
Did you know they are still ok to eat?

Bolting is where a plant tries to flower before you are ready for it.
Most of my red onions bolted this year for some reason but that doesn’t mean they are going to get wasted.

Unlike with leeks, the core of bolted onions doesn’t go really hard meaning they are still fine to cook with.

What they won’t be any good for is long term storage.
So harvest you bolted onions and either cook with them over the next couple of weeks, or, like me you can grate and freeze in just the same way I did with my garlic on my last Reel.

Im interested if anyone else has had an issue with bolting on red onions in particular, let me know?

Why is it worth saving tomato seeds in bulk at home?

Well if you store them somewhere dry at around room temp they will last a good 5 years and if you make the effort to store them in the fridge they will last much much longer.
This means you can have many years of tomato seeds from just one saving session.
Sounds well worth the effort to me!

To save tomato seeds in bulk at home, scoop out all the juicy bits with the seeds in, avoiding as much of the flesh and skin as possible.

Place in a container with a lid (to keep out the fruit flies) and leave to ferment for 3 days, it will get mouldy on top and pretty stinky but that’s just fine.

Pass through a sieve and rinse off all the putrid flesh leaving behind the lovely clean seeds.

Draw out the worst of the water from below with a tea towel and then tap out onto grease proof paper.

Spread out the seeds and let them dry, don’t forget to label them so you know what you’ve got.

Finally rub the seeds between your fingers so any clumps crumble apart and then store in a cool dry place.

Remember you can only do this with open pollinated seed, hybrid F1 seed won’t grow the same tomato you saved it from.
Happy seed saving guys!

Also called field beet, these sit somewhere between a beetroot and a sugarbeet and as such have a sweeter, less eathy flavour than our staple beetroot.

This beauty is a Mamouth Red, very much living up to its name but I also have a lovely yellow fleshed one.

Do you want a squash that gives you real bang for your buck?
We’ll check out my Sharks Fin Melon harvest of 64, yes 64 fruit from just one plant!

As if that’s not enough for you, they are by far the longest storing squash (well melon strictly speaking) we have come across, being perfectly good more than 2 years after harvest.

Structurally this is much like a watermelon inside but more like spaghetti squash in texture and it’s also not sweet like a standard squash.
This plant is all about texture which it retains when cooked, and if you are looking for a genuine meat alternative look no further.

Traditionally this is used as an ethical alternative to sharks fin soup (hence the name) which is a good indicator to how it can be used best.
We love it in a delicious warming ramen.

Yes we do have seeds but only a limited number, link in stories for anyone interested in trying this epically productive plant.

Fresh homegrown tomatoes in January?!
It’s true!

We are always in such a panic to chutney all our green tomatoes at the end of the season we forget that many will actually ripen given the chance.

I picked these Black Strawberry tomatoes back in October and since then they have sat in my jungle room where they have gradually ripened away.

I kept an eye on them, removed any that went bad and kept the fruit flies off and now I have home grown tomatoes in deep winter.

This is a similar concept to storage tomatoes which is something I will be growing a lot more of going forward to try and keep us eating fresh tomatoes as long as possible.

Not sweet like summer tomatoes but still packed with homegrown flavour!

Today I spent a beautifully day in my warm and sunny jungle room potting up chillies and peppers.

I wouldn’t usually use the pricking out method on these plants but I want a lot of each variety going forward so pricking out it is.

When I plant those little seedlings I bury them right up to the seed leaves.
Chillies and peppers are able to grow new roots out of their stems so this will ensure they have good strong root systems as they mature.

They will continue to grow on under grow lights on heat mats until the days warm up and get longer.

A reminder that it’s absolutely fine if you do not have grow lights, you will just need to wait around another month to start your capsicum seeds.
